  <section id="design">
    <h2>Platform &amp; Build Quality</h2>
    <p>We did not access the OLSP member dashboard firsthand, so we cannot describe the interface directly. The following is based on third-party walkthroughs and vendor descriptions.</p>

    <h3>Mega Builder — The Core Software</h3>
    <p>The most significant technology included at the Community Builders tier is Mega Builder: a white-label version of GoHighLevel, an established SaaS marketing platform used independently by marketing agencies worldwide. GoHighLevel's core capabilities are verifiable outside of OLSP, which is a meaningful trust signal compared to proprietary tools with no independent reference point.</p>
    <p>Within the OLSP context, Mega Builder reportedly includes TD Pages for building funnels and landing pages, a CRM with pipeline tracking for managing leads, an email autoresponder pre-loaded with sequences for OLSP products, calendar and booking automation, and deep integration with OLSP's affiliate tracking and commission system. Vendor materials claim this suite replaces $100–$300 per month of separate subscriptions to tools like standalone CRMs and email platforms. That is a <strong>vendor claim</strong> and depends on which external tools you would otherwise be paying for.</p>

    <h3>Community and Hub Sites</h3>
    <p>Community Builders unlocks the ability to create private OLSP communities with unique invite links — curated spaces for your recruited team and prospects within the OLSP platform. Members can also build public hub pages via TD Pages that act as a centralized resource hub for offers and content. Both tools are designed to keep your leads inside the OLSP ecosystem and give you a layer of audience and relationship ownership on top of OLSP's central system.</p>

    <h3>Long-Term Platform Considerations</h3>
    <p>OLSP Community Builders is entirely dependent on the OLSP ecosystem remaining active and maintaining its commission structure, training calendar, and software suite. Multiple independent reviewers note this as a structural risk: if OLSP changes its compensation plan, retires a product tier, or shuts down, members lose the infrastructure they've built their promotional workflows around. This dependency is a risk shared by most single-vendor "earn inside our ecosystem" platforms and should be weighed against the recurring cost.</p>
  </section>

