  <section id="faq">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <FaqItem question="Is OLSP Community Builders an MLM?">
      <p>OLSP is an affiliate marketing ecosystem, not a multi-level marketing company in the legal or regulatory sense — it does not require members to buy or hold inventory, and commissions derive from genuine product and software subscriptions. However, the tiered structure where you earn from your own sales and from the activity of affiliates you recruit does share structural characteristics with multi-tier affiliate programs that critics describe as MLM-like. Reddit discussion around OLSP includes active debate on this point, with some users calling it a "Ponzi" and others defending it as a legitimate affiliate system. No external regulatory determination has been made in the public record as of our research.</p>
    </FaqItem>
    <FaqItem question="What exactly does Mega Builder include?">
      <p>Mega Builder is a white-label version of GoHighLevel, an established SaaS marketing platform used by agencies worldwide. Within the OLSP context, it reportedly includes a funnel and page builder (TD Pages), a CRM with pipeline tracking, an email autoresponder pre-loaded with OLSP sequences, calendar and booking automation, and deep integration with OLSP's affiliate tracking. The underlying GoHighLevel platform is independently verifiable — this is a meaningful feature compared to proprietary tools with no public reference. Verify which specific features are active at your tier directly with OLSP, as configurations can differ from what promotional materials describe.</p>
    </FaqItem>
    <FaqItem question="Is Team Builders a better financial deal than Community Builders?">
      <p>Community Builders' monthly fee (~$197/month) adds up over time: after five months you've paid close to the reported ~$997 Team Builders lifetime price. The better financial choice depends on your budget, how certain you are about committing to the OLSP ecosystem long-term, and whether Team Builders' additional commission tiers are relevant to the products you plan to promote. If you're uncertain about long-term commitment, the Community Builders monthly subscription lets you exit without a large upfront outlay.</p>
    </FaqItem>
    <FaqItem question="Can a complete beginner join Community Builders directly?">
      <p>There is no technical eligibility requirement — anyone can pay for the upgrade. However, both vendor materials and independent reviewers consistently recommend against joining Community Builders without first completing and actively using the Megalink level. The tools and TOFFEE training are designed for members who already understand the OLSP promotional workflow, not for people simultaneously learning affiliate marketing basics. Jumping directly to Community Builders as a beginner adds a recurring cost before you have the foundational habits needed to justify it.</p>
    </FaqItem>
  </section>

